MPD, and a USB DAC.
If you have a growing digital collection of music titles, you might be
considering buying a network audio player to provide audiophile quality
playback. However, being excellent all-in-one and easy to set up devices,
network audio players still have limitations:
they have a built-in DAC, which you cannot swap;
they might not support some storage devices, such as HDD;
they might not support some audio formats, take DSD128 for example;
they are usually controlled with a mobile app, which might be inconvenient or
buggy;
they are rather expensive!
An alternative to a ready-made network audio player would be a PC with proper
software and a USB DAC.
When it comes to the software, my personal recommendation would be to go with
Music Player Daemon (MPD). It is an extremely flexible, powerful, server-side
application for playing music. MPD features:
support of ALSA output and hence bit-perfect playback;
a great variety of audio formats supported (plays anything, really);
a wide selection of clients available, from console to mobile apps, for remote
playback control.
And it is free! As is Linux.
My Personal Setup
I wanted to start with a Raspberry Pi or something similar, but in the end I
bought an Intel NUC mini PC unit, and installed RAM and SSD in it — payed less
than $250 for everything.
The NUC is running Debain Linux. I installed a VPN server and an NFS server to
make my media library available throughout the network, and a miniDLNA server
for video streaming. Finally, I installed MPD and configured it to output audio
via ALSA to the Arcam irDAC-II connected via USB.</p></div> <footer class="page-edit"><!----> <!----></footer> <!----> </main></div><div class="global-ui"></div></div>
